          "title": "The Deuteronomic indictment and the standard of David",
          "body": "The Deuteronomic Historian measures Solomon against two standards: the explicit covenant commands (Deut 17:17 — 'he shall not multiply wives') and the implicit standard of David his father (11:4, 6, 33, 34, 38). The reference to David is not nostalgic; it is theological. David was not sinless — his adultery and murder are narrated without softening in 2 Samuel 11-12. But David's heart was *shalem* (whole, complete, undivided) toward Yahweh — the same root as Solomon's name (*Shelomoh*, peace/wholeness). The great irony is that the man whose name means completeness is condemned for a heart that was not complete. The comparison with David teaches that the standard for covenant kingship is not sinless perfection but undivided, correctable loyalty — a heart that when it sins, confesses (Psalm 51), and returns. Solomon's tragedy is not that he sinned but that he never came back."
