          "title": "God's sovereignty over the adversaries",
          "body": "The three adversary narratives (11:14-40) are not political digressions from the theological argument — they are the theological argument made geopolitical. The LORD *raised up* Hadad (11:14); God *raised up* Rezon (11:23); God *raised up* Jeroboam (11:26-31 with Ahijah's oracle). In each case, a human instrument with his own history and grievance is the means by which God's declared sentence is administered. Hadad had waited in Egypt since childhood, nursing a royal Edomite bloodline through David's wars and all of Solomon's glory years, until the moment God's purposes required him. Rezon had built an Aramean power base in Damascus throughout Solomon's reign — a fact withheld from the narrative until the chapter of judgment. The Deuteronomic Historian's point is unambiguous: Israel's history is not driven by the geopolitical calculations of its neighbors but by the covenant administration of her God. The *satan* (adversary) in this chapter is always a human agent, but the appointment is always divine."
