          "title": "The torn cloak and prophetic word",
          "body": "The sign-act at the chapter's center (11:29-39) is one of the Old Testament's most dramatic prophetic performances. Ahijah of Shiloh — a prophet from the ancient sanctuary city of the ark's residence before Jerusalem — takes a new cloak and tears it into twelve pieces. The new cloak (not an old worn garment) represents the kingdom in its current wholeness; the tearing is the enacted decree of what God has determined. Ten pieces go to Jeroboam; one is retained for David's line; the arithmetic of mercy and judgment is made textile and visible. The prophetic sign-act has both performative and interpretive force in Old Testament theology — Ahijah does not merely predict the division; he enacts it in the prophetic speech-act tradition of Isaiah, Jeremiah, and Ezekiel. The word God speaks through His prophet is already doing what it declares. Jeroboam holds ten pieces of torn wool and understands: this is not political prophecy, it is divine appointment."
