          "body": "1 Kings 11 functions within the canon as both warning and hope. As warning, it answers the question every reader of 1 Kings 3-10 must eventually ask: if divine wisdom does not guarantee covenant faithfulness, what does? The answer is not wisdom but whole-hearted love — an undivided heart that holds fast (*davaq*) to Yahweh the way Solomon held fast to his wives. As hope, the chapter's repeated 'for the sake of David' and 'not always' (11:12, 13, 34, 36, 39) insist that the covenant is more durable than any individual king's failure. The Davidic lamp burns in Jerusalem through the divided monarchy, through the exile, through the Persian and Hellenistic periods, until it is finally identified in the Galilean rabbi who comes to Jerusalem not to build shrines on the Mount of Olives but to pray on it — and whose kingdom, unlike Solomon's, will not be torn from His hand."
